# {{.ProjectName}}

Generated by `wfkit init`.

This project expects `wfkit` to be installed locally from `devDependencies`, so everyone on the team can run the same CLI version through package scripts.

## Start here

Update `wfkit.json` with your real Webflow and GitHub settings.

If you just ran `wfkit init` without `--skip-install`, dependencies are already installed.
After cloning the project later on another machine, install them with:

```bash
{{.InstallCommand}}
```

Then:

```bash
{{.RunScript}} dev
```

Open `http://localhost:3000` to work against your proxied `.webflow.io` site locally.

## Use the generated scripts

- `{{.RunScript}} dev` starts the Webflow proxy and local Vite dev server
- `{{.RunScript}} build` builds production assets into `dist/assets`
- `{{.RunScript}} docs` publishes `docs/index.md` to the `{{.DocsPageSlug}}` Webflow page
- `{{.RunScript}} publish` builds, pushes, and updates Webflow production code
- `{{.RunScript}} lint` runs ESLint for scaffolded source files
- `{{.RunScript}} typecheck` runs TypeScript checks

## Project layout

```text
src/
  features/
    site-status.ts
  global/
    index.ts
    modules/
      site.global.ts
  pages/
    home/
      index.ts
  utils/
    dom.ts
    webflow.ts
build/
  webflow-vite-plugin.js
docs/
  index.md
dist/assets/
  wfkit-manifest.json
```

`src/global/index.ts` is your global entry.
`src/features/*` is where reusable Webflow behaviors should live.
`src/pages/*/index.ts` is where page-specific code lives.
`src/utils/webflow.ts` mounts features through the Webflow runtime and falls back safely outside Webflow.
`docs/index.md` is the default docs hub entry.
